
[1]basking-shark

   B'ASKING-SHARK, n. The sun-fish of the Irish; a species of squalus or
   shark. This fish is from three to twelve yards in length, or even
   longer. The upper jaw is much longer than the lower one; the tail is
   large and the upper part much longer than the lower; the skin is rough,
   of a deep leaden color on the back, and white on the belly. The fish
   weighs more than a thousand pounds, and affords a great quantity of
   oil, which is used for lamps, and to cure bruises, burns, and rheumatic
   complaints. It is viviparous, and frequents the northern seas. [See
   Squalus.]
